@flexiarg vsatlatarium/cluster-as-story
@title Cluster as Story, Node as Scene
@audience narrative system designers, digital library architects
@tone analytic
@style design-pattern
@sigils [🌌/文]
@references [vsatlas/connected-story-world vsatlas/non-destructive-relational-layers]

! conclusion:
  Represent each story as a spatial cluster of scene nodes so internal
  narrative structure is visible alongside inter-story connections.

  + context: You are designing a visualisation that must convey both within-story structure and between-story relationships at a glance. This does not apply to single-story views where internal navigation is sufficient.
  + IF:
    Viewers need to grasp both the shape of individual stories and how
    they relate to one another.

  + HOWEVER:
    Collapsing stories to single points hides internal richness;
    flattening all scenes to one level hides story boundaries.

  + THEN:
    Use a two-level layout: stories are clusters positioned on the dome
    via golden-spiral distribution, and scenes within each cluster are
    arranged by force-directed simulation around the cluster centre.
    Narrative arcs (within) and interpretive links (between) are drawn
    as distinct arc types.

  + BECAUSE:
    Two-level clustering preserves the part-whole relationship that
    makes a story more than a bag of scenes, while still exposing the
    relational fabric that VSATLAS adds across stories.

  + STATUS:
    status[ready]
    evidence[VSATLATARIUM two-level constellation — golden spiral + spring layout]

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Test legibility with 50+ stories to find the threshold where clusters overlap.]
    next[Experiment with alternative intra-cluster layouts (radial, timeline) for stories with strong sequence.]
